SIMPLE: tub
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Tub
<hw>Tub</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>tubbe</ets>; of
Dutch or Low German origin; cf. LG. <ets>tubbe</ets>, D.
<ets>tobbe</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An open wooden vessel formed
with staves, bottom, and hoops; a kind of short cask, half barrel, or
firkin, usually with but one head, -- used for various
purposes.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The amount which a tub contains, as a measure of
quantity; <as>as, a <ex>tub</ex> of butter; a <ex>tub</ex> of camphor,
which is about 1 cwt., etc</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Any structure shaped like a tub: as, a certain old
form of pulpit; a short, broad boat, etc., -- often used jocosely or
opprobriously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All being took up and busied, some in pulpits and some in
<qex>tubs</qex>, in the grand work of preaching and holding forth.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A sweating in a tub; a tub fast.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A small cask; <as>as, a <ex>tub</ex> of
gin</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A box or bucket in which coal or ore is sent up a
shaft; -- so called by miners.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Tub fast</b></col>, <cd>an old mode of treatment for the
venereal disease, by sweating in a close place, or tub, and
fasting.</cd> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <au>Shak.</au> -- <col><b>Tub
wheel</b></col>, <cd>a horizontal water wheel, usually in the form of a
short cylinder, to the circumference of which spiral vanes or floats,
placed radially, are attached, turned by the impact of one or more
streams of water, conducted so as to strike against the floats in the
direction of a tangent to the cylinder.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tub</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Tub
<hw>Tub</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Tubbed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Tubbing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To plant or set in a tub; <as>as,
to <ex>tub</ex> a plant</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tub</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Tub
<hw>Tub</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To make use of a bathing tub; to lie
or be in a bath; to bathe.</def> <mark>[Colloq.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Don't we all <qex>tub</qex> in England ?</q> <rj><qau>London
Spectator.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Tuba</ent>⟦br⟧
